{"title_page": "Wallace Roney", "text_new": "{{short description|American musician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{refimprove|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Wallace Roney\n| image            = Wallace Roney Pori Jazz 2012.JPG\n| image_upright    = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Roney at [[Pori Jazz]] festival in 2012\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1960|5|25}}\n| birth_place      = [[Philadelphia|Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| origin           = \n| death_date       = {{death date and age |2020|03|31|1960|05|25|mf=yes}}\n| death_place      = [[Paterson|Paterson, New Jersey]], U.S.\n| genre            = Jazz\n| occupation       = Musician\n| instrument       = Trumpet\n| years_active     = 1975\u20132020\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[Miles Davis]], [[Clark Terry]], [[Dizzy Gillespie]]\n| website          = {{URL|http://www.wallaceroney.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Wallace Roney''' (May 25, 1960 \u2013 March 31, 2020) was an American [[jazz]] ([[hard bop]] and [[post-bop]]) trumpeter.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/wallace-roney-mn0000813629/biography|title=Wallace Roney &#124; Biography & History|website=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2020/03/wallace-roney-dead/|title=Wallace Roney Dead: Miles Davis' Protege Dies from Covid-19 Complications|first=Paul|last=Farrell|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRoney took lessons from [[Clark Terry]] and [[Dizzy Gillespie]] and studied with [[Miles Davis]] from 1985 until the latter's death in 1991.  Wallace credited Davis as having helped to challenge and shape his creative approach to life as well as being his music instructor, mentor, and friend; he was the only trumpet player Davis personally mentored.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/31/824801424/wallace-roney-intrepid-jazz-trumpeter-dies-from-covid-19-complications-at-59|title=Wallace Roney, Intrepid Jazz Trumpeter, Dies From COVID-19 Complications At 59|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:Wallace Roney.jpg|thumb|left|Wallace Roney at Monterey Jazz Festival 9/92]]\nRoney was born in [[Philadelphia]] and attended [[Howard University]] and [[Berklee College of Music]] in [[Boston, Massachusetts]], after graduating from the [[Duke Ellington School of the Arts]] of the [[District of Columbia Public Schools|D. C. Public Schools]], where he studied trumpet with Langston Fitzgerald of the [[Baltimore Symphony Orchestra]].<ref name=\":3\" /> Found to have [[perfect pitch]] at the age of four, Wallace began his musical and trumpet studies at Philadelphia's Settlement School of Music.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHe studied with trumpeter Sigmund Hering of the [[Philadelphia Orchestra]] for three years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9348081/wallace-roney-dead-coronavirus|title=Wallace Roney, Celebrated Jazz Trumpeter, Dies From Coronavirus at 59|date=March 31, 2020|website=Billboard|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> Hering regularly presented Wallace at recitals at the Settlement School, and with the Philadelphia Brass Ensemble, during his studies in Philadelphia.\n\nWhen he entered the Duke Ellington School, Roney had already made his recording debut at age 15 with Nation and Haki Mahbuti, and at that time met, among others, [[Bill Hardman]], [[Valery Ponomarev]], [[Woody Shaw]] (who befriended him), [[Johnny Coles]] and [[Freddie Hubbard]]. He played with the [[Cedar Walton]] Quartet featuring [[Billy Higgins]], [[Sam Jones (musician)|Sam Jones]], and [[Philly Joe Jones]] at 16 years of age with the encouragement of his high school teacher.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nRoney attained distinction as a gifted local performer in the Washington, D.C area. In 1979 and 1980, Roney won the ''[[DownBeat]]'' Award for Best Young Jazz Musician of the Year, and in 1989 and 1990 the ''DownBeat'' Magazine's Critic's Poll for Best Trumpeter to Watch.\n\nIn 1983, while taking part in a tribute to [[Miles Davis]] at \"[[The Bottom Line (venue)|The Bottom Line]]\" in Manhattan, he met his idol.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Staudter|first=Thomas|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/09/09/nyregion/making-jazz-and-family-home-and-the-road-work-together.html|title=Making Jazz and Family, Home and the Road Work Together|date=September 9, 2001|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 1, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> \"He [Davis] asked me what kind of trumpet I had,\" Roney told ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine, \"and I told him none. So he gave me one of his.\" In 1984 and 1985, he was forced to play in Latin dance and reception bands, as the New York clubs, once a prominent part of the jazz scene, had mostly disappeared. But in 1986, he received a pair of calls, in the same month, to tour with drummers [[Tony Williams (drummer)|Tony Williams]] and [[Art Blakey]], after which Roney became one of the most in-demand trumpet players on the professional circuit.\n\nIn 1986, he succeeded [[Terence Blanchard]] in Blakey's [[Jazz Messengers]].<ref name=\":0\" /> In the late 1980s and early 1990s, he was an integral part of Williams's quintet. In 1991, Roney played with Davis at the [[Montreux Jazz Festival]]. After Davis's death that year, Roney toured in memoriam with Davis alumni [[Wayne Shorter]], [[Herbie Hancock]], [[Ron Carter]] and Tony Williams and recorded an album, ''[[A Tribute to Miles]]'', for which they won a [[Grammy Award]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/31/us/wallace-roney-death-covid-19/index.html|title=Legendary jazz trumpeter Wallace Roney dies of complications from coronavirus|author1=Duarte Mendonca |author2=Jennifer Hauser|website=CNN|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRoney learned his craft directly from Miles Davis.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> Critics have taken Roney to task for sounding too similar to his idol. Roney recorded his debut album as a leader, ''Verses'', on [[Muse Records]] in 1987. A number of albums on Muse, [[Warner Bros. Records]] and [[Concord Records]]/[[Stretch Records]] followed, and by the time he turned 40 in 2000 Roney had been documented on over 250 audio recordings. His album titles from the 2000s include ''Mystikal'' (2005) and ''[[Jazz (Wallace Roney)|Jazz]]'' (2007) on [[HighNote Records]]. His two most recent albums are ''A Place in Time'' (HighNote 2016) and ''Blue Dawn - Blue Nights'' (HighNote 2019),<ref name=\":3\" /> which features his nephew, drummer [[Kojo Roney]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nWallace Roney was the son of Wallace Roney, [[United States Marshals Service|U.S. Marshal]] and President of the [[American Federation of Government Employees]] Local 102, grandson of Philadelphia musician Roosevelt Sherman, and older brother of tenor and soprano saxophonist [[Antoine Roney]].<ref name=\":3\" /> In 1995, Roney married pianist [[Geri Allen]], with whom he had two daughters and a son.<ref name=\":1\" /> The marriage ended prior to Allen's death in 2017.<ref name=\"Guard\">{{cite news |last=Fordham |first=John |date=July 3, 2017 |title=Geri Allen Obituary|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/jul/03/geri-allen-obituary |work=The Guardian |location= |accessdate=}}</ref> The two artists collaborated on records on many occasions during the 1990s and 2000s, on records released under each artist's name.\n\nEarlier in his life, Roney had been a resident of  [[Montclair, New Jersey]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Death==\nWallace Roney died at the age of 59 on March 31, 2020, at St. Joseph's University Medical Center in Paterson, New Jersey. The cause was complications arising from [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Wallace Roney Dead: Miles Davis' Protege Dies from Covid-19 Complications |url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2020/03/wallace-roney-dead/ |publisher=heavy. |accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Movie credits==\n*2001 - ''The Visit'' - Jordan Walker-Perlman - music arrangement\n*1996 - ''Love Jones'' - music arrangement\n\n==Discography==\n===As leader===\n*1987 \u2013 ''[[Verses (album)|Verses]]'' ([[Muse Records|Muse]]) \n*1988 \u2013 ''[[Intuition (Wallace Roney album)|Intuition]]'' (Muse)\n*1989 \u2013 ''[[The Standard Bearer]]'' (Muse)\n*1989 \u2212 ''What's New'' ([[Nippon Crown]]) released 2016\n*1990 \u2013 ''[[Obsession (Wallace Roney album)|Obsession]]'' (Muse)\n*1991 \u2013 ''[[Seth Air]]'' (Muse)\n*1993 \u2013 ''[[Munchin']]'' (Muse) \n*1993 \u2013 ''[[Crunchin']]'' (Muse)\n*1994 \u2013 ''[[Mist\u00e9rios]]'' ([[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]) arranged and conducted by [[Gil Goldstein]]\n*1995 \u2013 ''Wallace Roney Quintet'' (Warner Bros.) with Antoine Roney, [[Carlos McKinney]], Clarence Seay, Eric Allen\n*1996 \u2013 ''Village'' (Warner Bros.) with Antoine Roney, [[Chick Corea]], Geri Allen, Clarence Seay, [[Lenny White]], [[Michael Brecker]], [[Pharoah Sanders]], [[Robert Irving III]], Steve Berrios\n*2001 \u2013 ''No Room for Argument'' ([[Concord Jazz]]) with Geri Allen, [[Adam Holzman (keyboardist)|Adam Holzman]], Antoine Roney, Lenny White, [[Buster Williams]], Steve Hall\n* 2003 - ''No Job Too Big or Small'' ([[Savoy Records|Savoy]]) with Eric Allen, Geri Allen, Cindy Blackman, [[Kenny Washington (musician)|Kenny Washington]], Donald Brown, [[Ron Carter]], many others\n*2004 \u2013 ''Prototype'' ([[HighNote Records|Highnote]]) with Antoine Roney, [[Don Byron]], [[Clifton Anderson]], Geri Allen, Adam Holzman, [[Matt Garrison]], Eric Allen, [[DJ Logic]]\n*2005 \u2013 ''Mystikal'' (Highnote) with Antoine Roney, Geri Allen, Adam Holzman, Matt Garrison, Eric Allen, [[Bobby Thomas]],  [[Val Jeanty]]\n*2007 \u2013 ''[[Jazz (Wallace Roney)|Jazz]]''  (Highnote) with [[Antoine Roney]], [[Geri Allen]], [[Robert Irving III]], Rashaan Carter, Eric Allen, [[Val Jeanty]]\n*2010 \u2013 ''If Only for One Night''  (Highnote)\n*2012 \u2013 ''Home''  (Highnote)\n*2013 \u2013 ''Understanding''  (Highnote)\n*2016 \u2013 ''A Place In Time''  (Highnote)\n*2019 \u2013 ''Blue Dawn \u2013 Blue Nights'' (Highnote)\n\n===As sideman===\n'''With [[Geri Allen]]'''\n*''[[Maroons (album)|Maroons]]'' (Blue Note, 1992)\n*''[[Eyes in the Back of Your Head]]'' (Blue Note, 1997)\n*''[[The Gathering (Geri Allen album)|The Gathering]]'' (Verve, 1998)\n*''[[Timeless Portraits and Dreams]]'' ([[Telarc International|Telarc]], 2006)\n'''With [[Kenny Barron]]'''\n*''[[What If? (Kenny Barron album)|What If?]]'' (Enja, 1986)\n'''With [[Cindy Blackman]]'''\n*''[[Arcane (album)|Arcane]]'' (Muse, 1987)\n*''[[Code Red (Cindy Blackman album)|Code Red]]'' (Muse, 1990 [1992])\n'''With [[Art Blakey]]'''\n*''[[Killer Joe (George Kawaguchi & Art Blakey album)|Killer Joe]]'' (Union Jazz, 1981) \u2013 with George Kawaguchi\n*''[[Feeling Good (Art Blakey album)|Feeling Good]]'' (Delos, 1986)\n'''With [[Chick Corea]]'''\n*''[[Remembering Bud Powell]]'' (Stretch, 1997)\n'''With [[Joey DeFrancesco]]'''\n*''[[Where Were You?]]'' (Columbia, 1990)\n'''With [[Ricky Ford]]'''\n*''[[Interpretations (album)|Interpretations]]'' (Muse, 1982)\n'''With [[Dizzy Gillespie]]'''\n*''[[To Diz with Love]]'' (Telarc, 1992)\n'''With [[Vincent Herring]]'''\n*''[[Evidence (Vincent Herring album)|Evidence]]'' (Landmark, 1991)\n*''[[Dawnbird]]'' (Landmark, 1993)\n*''[[Simple Pleasure (Vincent Herring album)|Simple Pleasure]]'' (HighNote, 2001)\n'''With [[Helen Merrill]]'''\n*''Brownie-A Homage To Clifford Brown'' (Verve, 1994)\n'''With [[Jarmo Savolainen]]'''\n* ''First Sight'' (Timeless, 1992)\n'''With [[James Spaulding]]'''\n*''[[Brilliant Corners (James Spaulding album)|Brilliant Corners]]'' (Muse, 1988)\n'''WIth [[Superblue (band)|Superblue]]'''\n*''Superblue 2'' (1989, Blue Note)\n'''With [[Tony Williams (drummer)|Tony Williams]]'''\n*''Civilization'' (1986, Blue Note)\n''With Powerhouse''\n* \u201cPasa Tiempo\u201d (2002, Evidence Music) with Joe Louis Walker, produced by Carla Olson and Brian Brinkerhoff.\n*''In an Ambient Way'' (2015, Chesky Records)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wallaceroney.com/ Official website]\n* [http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/musician.php?id=3905 Profile], AllAboutJazz.com\n* [http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/article.php?id=19714 Fulfilling the Promise]\n* [https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4072431 Following in Miles Davis' Footsteps], npr.org\n* [http://arts.enotes.com/contemporary-musicians/roney-wallace-biography Biography], enotes.com\n* [https://www.namm.org/library/oral-history/wallace-roney Wallace Roney Interview] NAMM Oral History Library (2018)\n* {{Discogs artist|Wallace Roney}}\n\n{{Jazz Messengers}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roney, Wallace}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Post-bop trumpeters]]\n[[Category:Hard bop trumpeters]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:American jazz trumpeters]]\n[[Category:American male trumpeters]]\n[[Category:American jazz composers]]\n[[Category:Male jazz composers]]\n[[Category:Berklee College of Music alumni]]\n[[Category:Howard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:The Jazz Messengers members]]\n[[Category:Muse Records artists]]\n[[Category:HighNote Records artists]]\n[[Category:Warner Records artists]]\n[[Category:African-American jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Montclair, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Superblue (band) members]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n[[Category:20th-century trumpeters]]\n[[Category:20th-century American musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century trumpeters]]\n[[Category:21st-century American musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American musician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{refimprove|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Wallace Roney\n| image            = Wallace Roney Pori Jazz 2012.JPG\n| image_upright    = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Roney at [[Pori Jazz]] festival in 2012\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1960|5|25}}\n| birth_place      = [[Philadelphia|Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| origin           = \n| death_date       = {{death date and age |2020|03|31|1960|05|25|mf=yes}}\n| death_place      = [[Paterson|Paterson, New Jersey]], U.S.\n| genre            = Jazz\n| occupation       = Musician\n| instrument       = Trumpet\n| years_active     = 1975\u20132020\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[Miles Davis]], [[Clark Terry]], [[Dizzy Gillespie]]\n| website          = {{URL|http://www.wallaceroney.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Wallace Roney''' (May 25, 1960 \u2013 March 31, 2020) was an American jazz ([[hard bop]] and [[post-bop]]) trumpeter.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/wallace-roney-mn0000813629/biography|title=Wallace Roney &#124; Biography & History|website=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2020/03/wallace-roney-dead/|title=Wallace Roney Dead: Miles Davis' Protege Dies from Covid-19 Complications|first=Paul|last=Farrell|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRoney took lessons from [[Clark Terry]] and [[Dizzy Gillespie]] and studied with [[Miles Davis]] from 1985 until the latter's death in 1991.  Wallace credited Davis as having helped to challenge and shape his creative approach to life as well as being his music instructor, mentor, and friend; he was the only trumpet player Davis personally mentored.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/31/824801424/wallace-roney-intrepid-jazz-trumpeter-dies-from-covid-19-complications-at-59|title=Wallace Roney, Intrepid Jazz Trumpeter, Dies From COVID-19 Complications At 59|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:Wallace Roney.jpg|thumb|left|Wallace Roney at Monterey Jazz Festival 9/92]]\nRoney was born in [[Philadelphia]] and attended [[Howard University]] and [[Berklee College of Music]] in [[Boston, Massachusetts]], after graduating from the [[Duke Ellington School of the Arts]] of the [[District of Columbia Public Schools|D. C. Public Schools]], where he studied trumpet with Langston Fitzgerald of the [[Baltimore Symphony Orchestra]].<ref name=\":3\" /> Found to have [[perfect pitch]] at the age of four, Wallace began his musical and trumpet studies at Philadelphia's Settlement School of Music.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHe studied with trumpeter Sigmund Hering of the [[Philadelphia Orchestra]] for three years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9348081/wallace-roney-dead-coronavirus|title=Wallace Roney, Celebrated Jazz Trumpeter, Dies From Coronavirus at 59|date=March 31, 2020|website=Billboard|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> Hering regularly presented Wallace at recitals at the Settlement School, and with the Philadelphia Brass Ensemble, during his studies in Philadelphia.\n\nWhen he entered the Duke Ellington School, Roney had already made his recording debut at age 15 with Nation and Haki Mahbuti, and at that time met, among others, [[Bill Hardman]], [[Valery Ponomarev]], [[Woody Shaw]] (who befriended him), [[Johnny Coles]] and [[Freddie Hubbard]]. He played with the [[Cedar Walton]] Quartet featuring [[Billy Higgins]], [[Sam Jones (musician)|Sam Jones]], and [[Philly Joe Jones]] at 16 years of age with the encouragement of his high school teacher.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nRoney attained distinction as a gifted local performer in the Washington, D.C area. In 1979 and 1980, Roney won the ''[[DownBeat]]'' Award for Best Young Jazz Musician of the Year, and in 1989 and 1990 the ''DownBeat'' Magazine's Critic's Poll for Best Trumpeter to Watch.\n\nIn 1983, while taking part in a tribute to [[Miles Davis]] at \"[[The Bottom Line (venue)|The Bottom Line]]\" in Manhattan, he met his idol.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Staudter|first=Thomas|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/09/09/nyregion/making-jazz-and-family-home-and-the-road-work-together.html|title=Making Jazz and Family, Home and the Road Work Together|date=September 9, 2001|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 1, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> \"He [Davis] asked me what kind of trumpet I had,\" Roney told ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine, \"and I told him none. So he gave me one of his.\" In 1984 and 1985, he was forced to play in Latin dance and reception bands, as the New York clubs, once a prominent part of the jazz scene, had mostly disappeared. But in 1986, he received a pair of calls, in the same month, to tour with drummers [[Tony Williams (drummer)|Tony Williams]] and [[Art Blakey]], after which Roney became one of the most in-demand trumpet players on the professional circuit.\n\nIn 1986, he succeeded [[Terence Blanchard]] in Blakey's [[Jazz Messengers]].<ref name=\":0\" /> In the late 1980s and early 1990s, he was an integral part of Williams's quintet. In 1991, Roney played with Davis at the [[Montreux Jazz Festival]]. After Davis's death that year, Roney toured in memoriam with Davis alumni [[Wayne Shorter]], [[Herbie Hancock]], [[Ron Carter]] and Tony Williams and recorded an album, ''[[A Tribute to Miles]]'', for which they won a [[Grammy Award]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/31/us/wallace-roney-death-covid-19/index.html|title=Legendary jazz trumpeter Wallace Roney dies of complications from coronavirus|author1=Duarte Mendonca |author2=Jennifer Hauser|website=CNN|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRoney learned his craft directly from Miles Davis.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> Critics have taken Roney to task for sounding too similar to his idol. Roney recorded his debut album as a leader, ''Verses'', on [[Muse Records]] in 1987. A number of albums on Muse, [[Warner Bros. Records]] and [[Concord Records]]/[[Stretch Records]] followed, and by the time he turned 40 in 2000 Roney had been documented on over 250 audio recordings. His album titles from the 2000s include ''Mystikal'' (2005) and ''[[Jazz (Wallace Roney)|Jazz]]'' (2007) on [[HighNote Records]]. His two most recent albums are ''A Place in Time'' (HighNote 2016) and ''Blue Dawn - Blue Nights'' (HighNote 2019),<ref name=\":3\" /> which features his nephew, drummer [[Kojo Roney]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nWallace Roney was the son of Wallace Roney, [[United States Marshals Service|U.S. Marshal]] and President of the [[American Federation of Government Employees]] Local 102, grandson of Philadelphia musician Roosevelt Sherman, and older brother of tenor and soprano saxophonist [[Antoine Roney]].<ref name=\":3\" /> In 1995, Roney married pianist [[Geri Allen]], with whom he had two daughters and a son.<ref name=\":1\" /> The marriage ended prior to Allen's death in 2017.<ref name=\"Guard\">{{cite news |last=Fordham |first=John |date=July 3, 2017 |title=Geri Allen Obituary|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/jul/03/geri-allen-obituary |work=The Guardian |location= |accessdate=}}</ref> The two artists collaborated on records on many occasions during the 1990s and 2000s, on records released under each artist's name.\n\nEarlier in his life, Roney had been a resident of  [[Montclair, New Jersey]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Death==\nWallace Roney died at the age of 59 on March 31, 2020, at St. Joseph's University Medical Center in Paterson, New Jersey. The cause was comp